raphy -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTechnology has long been an essential consideration in public discussions of the environment, with the focus overwhelmingly on creating new tools and techniques. In more recent years, however, activists, researchers, and policymakers have increasingly turned to mobilizing older technologies in their pursuit of sustainability. In fascinating case studies ranging from the Early Modern secondhand trade to utopian visions of human-powered vehicles, the contributions gathered here explore the historical fortunes of two such technologies—bicycling and waste recycling—tracing their development over time and providing valuable context for the policy successes and failures of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBicyclesxScrapping. 0aCyclingxEnvironmental aspects. 0aCyclingxHistory. 0aRecycling (Waste, etc.)xEnvironmental aspects. 0aRecycling (Waste, etc.)xHistory. 0aRecycling (Waste, etc.). 0aSalvage (Waste, etc.). 0aSustainability. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aactivists.  abicycling and waste recycling.  acontext for policy today.  aexploration of bicycling.  aexploration of waste recycling.  ahistorical.  amobilizing older technologies.  apolicymakers.  apublic discussions of environment.  apursuit of sustainability.  aresearchers.  atracing development.1 aBruhèze, Adri Albert de la, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmanuel, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedel, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGille, Zsuzsa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Hans Peter, econ